 =20
    <h1 class=3D"post-title" itemprop=3D"headline">
      x509 Certificate Manual Signature Verification
    </h1>
 =20
  <div class=3D"postShorten-meta post-meta">
  <time itemprop=3D"datePublished" datetime=3D"2017-02-03T00:00:00Z">
   =20
  February 3, 2017

  </time>
 =20
 =20
 =20
    <span>in</span>
   =20
      <a class=3D"category-link" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/categories/se=
curity">security</a>,=20
   =20
      <a class=3D"category-link" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/categories/en=
cryption">encryption</a>
   =20
 =20


</div>

</div>
         =20
          <div class=3D"post-content markdown" itemprop=3D"articleBody">
            <div class=3D"main-content-wrap">
              <p>While going through the manual of <a href=3D"https://www.o=
penssl.org/docs/man1.1.0/">openssl</a>, I thought it would be a good exerci=
se to understand the signature verification process for educational purpose=
s. As a fruit to my labor, I would also develop a simple script to automate=
 the process.
</p>

<h1 id=3D"table-of-contents">Table of Contents</h1><nav id=3D"TableOfConten=
ts">
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#what-does-signing-a-certificate-mean">What Does =E2=80=9CS=
igning a Certificate=E2=80=9D Mean?</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#the-verification-process">The Verification Process</a>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#obtaining-the-issuer-s-public-key">Obtaining the Issuer=E2=
=80=99s Public Key</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#extracting-the-signature">Extracting the Signature</a></li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#decrypting-the-signature-rsa">Decrypting the Signature (RS=
A)</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#hashing-the-original-signature">Hashing the Original Signa=
ture</a></li>
</ul></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/02/x509-certificate-manual-signatu=
re-verification/#the-finished-script">The Finished Script</a></li>
</ul>
</nav>

<h1 id=3D"what-does-signing-a-certificate-mean">What Does =E2=80=9CSigning =
a Certificate=E2=80=9D Mean?</h1>

<p>A <strong>Certificate Authority (CA)</strong> utilizes <strong>asymmetri=
c cryptography</strong> to form a key pair. This key pair is usually referr=
ed to as the <em>public</em> key and the <strong>private</strong> key. Mess=
ages encrypted with one key, can only be decrypted with the other key. The =
public key is advertised and known to all, however the private key is kept =
secret and should only been known by the CA. When a <strong>Certificate Aut=
hority (CA)</strong> signs a certificate, what it actually does is <strong>=
hash</strong> the certificate then <strong>encrypt that hash</strong> with =
it=E2=80=99s private key. This hex code is then embedded into the certifica=
te along with information on how it was derived called the <code>Signature =
Algorithm</code>. Therefore, in order for one to <strong>verify</strong> th=
at a certificate was signed by a specific CA, we would only need to possess=
 the following:</p>

<blockquote>
<ul>
<li>the public key of the CA (issuer)</li>
<li>the <strong>Signature</strong> and <strong>Algorithm</strong> used to g=
enerate signature</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>

<h1 id=3D"the-verification-process">The Verification Process</h1>

<p>Obtaining the two listed items above is not a difficult task. Let=E2=80=
=99s examine how we would do this manually</p>

<h2 id=3D"obtaining-the-issuer-s-public-key">Obtaining the Issuer=E2=80=99s=
 Public Key</h2>

<p>The issuer of a x.509 certificate should have it=E2=80=99s own x.509 cer=
tificate (that=E2=80=99s also signed if it=E2=80=99s an Intermediate CA, or=
 slef signed if Root CA) to prove it=E2=80=99s authenticity. Once obtaining=
 this certificate, we can extract the public key with the following <code>o=
penssl</code> command:</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl x509 -in /tmp/rsa=
-4096-x509.pem -noout -pubkey &gt; /tmp/issuer-pub.pem
</code></pre>

<h2 id=3D"extracting-the-signature">Extracting the Signature</h2>

<p>Now let=E2=80=99s take a look at the signed certificate. The signature (=
along with algorithm) can be viewed from the <strong>signed certificate</st=
rong> using <code>openssl</code>:</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl x509 -in /tmp/ec-=
secp384r1-x509-signed.pem -noout -text
...
Signature Algorithm: sha384WithRSAEncryption
     ad:<span class=3D"built_in">cd</span>:dd:71:cf:8a:79:2c:2d:86:5b:a2:08=
:7e:00:e0:28:30:
     17:f3:b0:75:a6:12:46:<span class=3D"built_in">fc</span>:f8:75:9c:4a:57=
:2f:89:f9:8a:c6:
     03:e4:58:fa:c4:53:13:a7:67:18:60:17:<span class=3D"built_in">fc</span>=
:0d:e4:1a:ba:86:
     fd:14:a7:a5:cb:98:a3:d3:ea:40:a8:71:eb:<span class=3D"built_in">cd</sp=
an>:07:b7:e3:16:
     33:8d:ad:45:9f:ca:c7:ca:77:0a:ec:10:42:2a:85:8d:79:de:
     f0:a8:af:38:bc:70:2d:c1:5c:d7:b7:bb:a3:e8:5c:44:d3:89:
     a6:f0:00:8a:b7:1f:df:fd:5b:2a:9e:d3:9c:5f:ec:ad:7a:b8:
     5b:3b:6c:f5:8a:9c:4f:e5:84:d1:c9:ba:af:d5:9c:75:e8:43:
     17:2f:3c:be:e2:49:ef:6a:e1:28:73:f6:57:aa:4e:ec:a3:f9:
     7d:6f:c5:ce:83:20:<span class=3D"built_in">fc</span>:51:e0:3b:9f:7b:51=
:06:d3:29:28:08:
     19:99:2b:ca:fb:9e:7c:e9:5e:38:89:ec:71:f8:a4:aa:be:e0:
     1f:65:ed:24:d7:c0:13:aa:0c:f4:b6:f1:24:62:85:38:ac:05:
     f0:d0:de:69:91:dd:98:9d:9a:46:10:30:ac:6a:6a:20:d5:3c:
     c6:10:b4:2b:aa:d9:38:58:07:f2:41:12:23:45:1c:a8:ca:41:
     11:f2:fd:dd:6f:1a:83:ba:4e:ff:ef:b2:0a:7c:32:9e:0d:6b:
     01:17:76:69:59:9c:25:90:54:3d:08:f3:e9:3d:48:14:11:1d:
     09:59:6e:a9:22:1b:f5:c2:80:ee:4d:e7:f5:df:0a:b2:27:f3:
     05:68:3e:23:99:64:bb:d9:dc:25:95:1a:5f:b5:be:7d:0e:b9:
     47:e4:c6:34:0c:22:0a:ad:d0:c5:f9:be:cb:e3:c9:ca:71:d3:
     ea:f6:62:33:2f:08:c4:1e:d6:1e:aa:4b:5c:dd:bc:66:43:18:
     d9:56:68:93:<span class=3D"built_in">cd</span>:3a:ef:51:b3:67:8a:e9:bd=
:07:04:95:23:10:
     6c:42:2e:0d:28:a8:b4:c1:81:ba:1b:7e:9d:5c:48:16:6c:04:
     de:53:e6:7d:aa:cb:52:dd:8f:55:8d:09:1f:cf:32:70:ec:81:
     ea:00:07:52:8d:95:2b:b8:b6:ac:b6:36:0a:fd:02:f3:0e:42:
     20:1f:ce:1b:ba:c7:f4:aa:01:53:fb:af:9c:b5:e2:d5:61:7e:
     3c:2b:16:de:22:2b:43:13:f8:5a:6e:ab:c2:0a:85:96:6f:7b:
     b3:ef:49:0f:5f:bf:01:e9:52:f8:de:44:12:23:f5:e6:78:de:
     f6:e0:40:8e:97:89:45:92:f7:73:ee:41:71:7a:7c:de:79:10:
     f2:db:c3:86:85:3c:ac:fe
</code></pre>

<p>In the above example, we can tell by the algorithm name <code>sha384With=
RSAEncryption</code> that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2">S=
HA-384</a> is the cryptographic hash function used and that it was encrypte=
d via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_(cryptosystem)">RSA</a>.=
</p>

<p>We can take this hex and dump it to disk as a binary like this:</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs"><span class=3D"comment">#=
 extract hex of signature</span>
SIGNATURE_HEX=3D$(openssl x509 -in /tmp/ec-secp384r1-x509-signed.pem -text =
-noout -certopt ca_default -certopt no_validity -certopt no_serial -certopt=
 no_subject -certopt no_extensions -certopt no_signame | grep -v <span clas=
s=3D"string">'Signature Algorithm'</span> | tr <span class=3D"_">-d</span> =
<span class=3D"string">'[:space:]:'</span>)

<span class=3D"comment"># create signature dump</span>
<span class=3D"built_in">echo</span> <span class=3D"variable">${SIGNATURE_H=
EX}</span> | xxd -r -p &gt; /tmp/cert-sig.bin
</code></pre>

<h2 id=3D"decrypting-the-signature-rsa">Decrypting the Signature (RSA)</h2>

<p>Now that we have both the encrypted dump of the signature as well as the=
 public key of the issuer. We can decrypt the signature like so:</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl rsautl -verify -i=
nkey /tmp/issuer-pub.pem -in /tmp/cert-sig.bin -pubin &gt; /tmp/cert-sig-de=
crypted.bin
</code></pre>

<p>We can now finally view the hash with <code>openssl</code></p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl asn1parse -inform=
 der -in /tmp/cert-sig-decrypted.bin
0:d=3D0  hl=3D2 l=3D  65 cons: SEQUENCE         =20
2:d=3D1  hl=3D2 l=3D  13 cons: SEQUENCE         =20
4:d=3D2  hl=3D2 l=3D   9 prim: OBJECT            :sha384
15:d=3D2  hl=3D2 l=3D   0 prim: NULL             =20
17:d=3D1  hl=3D2 l=3D  48 prim: OCTET STRING      [HEX DUMP]:0C8EDBABEA1EAF=
2DB57A2A7CC29E2AAA9103167659572DFE10C0D7FF62BA74EC5481D6F049B956775E2BA3E11=
C5A046A
</code></pre>

<p>The digest is in the last line: <code>0C8EDBABEA1EAF2DB57A2A7CC29E2AAA91=
03167659572DFE10C0D7FF62BA74EC5481D6F049B956775E2BA3E11C5A046A</code></p>

<h2 id=3D"hashing-the-original-signature">Hashing the Original Signature</h=
2>

<p>Now that we got a hash of the orginal certificate, we need to verify if =
we can obtain the same hash by using the same hashing function (in this cas=
e SHA-384). In order to do that, we need to extract just the body of the si=
gned certificate. Which, in our case, is everything but the signature. The =
start of the body is always the first digit of the second line of the follo=
wing command:</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl asn1parse -i -in =
/tmp/ec-secp384r1-x509-signed.pem
    0:d=3D0  hl=3D4 l=3D 856 cons: SEQUENCE         =20
    4:d=3D1  hl=3D4 l=3D 320 cons:  SEQUENCE    =20
...    =20
</code></pre>

<p>We can extract this data and store it to disk like so:</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl asn1parse -in /tm=
p/ec-secp384r1-x509-signed.pem -strparse 4 -out /tmp/cert-body.bin -noout
</code></pre>

<p>Finally, we can run this through the same hashing function to determine =
the digest</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs">openssl dgst -sha384 /tmp=
/cert-body.bin
SHA384(/tmp/cert-body.bin)=3D 0c8edbabea1eaf2db57a2a7cc29e2aaa9103167659572=
dfe10c0d7ff62ba74ec5481d6f049b956775e2ba3e11c5a046a
</code></pre>

<p>As you can see, <strong>both hashes match</strong>, so we can now confir=
m that:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>/tmp/rsa-4096-x509.pem <strong>did sign</strong> /tmp/ec-secp384r1-x509-=
signed.pem</p>
</blockquote>

<h1 id=3D"the-finished-script">The Finished Script</h1>

<p>Now that we went through that manual process, I have put together a scri=
pt which undergoes a similar process to determine the valididty of a signat=
ure. Now in the real world, your browser will be tasked with validating a c=
hain of certificates not just the certificate that signed your domain=E2=80=
=99s cert. This script only checks if CERT A signed CERT B.
</p><div class=3D"alert warning ">
  <p>This script should not be relied upon in any shape, way or form. Simpl=
y educational.</p>
</div><p></p>

<p>Here is an example of how to use this script</p>

<pre><code class=3D"language-bash codeblock hljs"><span class=3D"comment">#=
 supply the signed cert (-s) and issuer's cert (-i) in pem encoding</span>
sh x509-cert-sig-verify.sh -i /tmp/rsa-4096-x509.pem <span class=3D"_">-s</=
span> /tmp/ec-secp384r1-x509-signed.pem

Issuer Certificate: /tmp/rsa-4096-x509.pem
Signed Certificate: /tmp/ec-secp384r1-x509-signed.pem
Verified OK

<span class=3D"comment"># when no arguments supplied</span>
sh x509-cert-sig-verify.sh
  Missing REQUIRED option -i &lt;ISSUER_CERTIFICATE&gt;

