       =20
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/=
08/bootstrapping-hyperledger-fabric-1.0/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Bootstrapping Hyperledger Fabri=
c 1.0</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Aug 8, 2017
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p>I a=
m proud to say that I have been working with the <a href=3D"https://www.hyp=
erledger.org/projects/fabric">Hyperledger Fabric</a> project nearly since i=
t=E2=80=99s inception almost two years ago. While frustrating at times in t=
he beginning (as is the case with most open-source, popular, and pre-alpha =
software), I have grown to enjoy working with the Fabric. It has improved m=
y skills in a variety of areas such as golang, docker, encryption, pkcs11, =
continuous integration, and many more. Since the Fabric recently went 1.0, =
this blog post will focus on how to bootstrap the fabric without the aid of=
 <code>cryptogen</code> tool.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/=
04/syncthing---why-you-should-be-using-it/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Syncthing - Why You Should be U=
sing it</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Apr 4, 2017
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p>Cho=
osing a secure file syncing application has never been easier. After evalua=
ting a variety of options such <a href=3D"https://www.dropbox.com/">Dropbox=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://owncloud.org/">OwnCloud</a>, and <a href=3D"https:=
//www.seafile.com/">Seafile</a> for <strong>over 5 years</strong>, the jour=
ney is finally over. I have found the best option - <a href=3D"https://sync=
thing.net/">Syncthing</a>. Let me explain why you should consider it.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/=
03/building-tiny-secure-docker-containers/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Building Tiny Secure Docker Con=
tainers</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Mar 3, 2017
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p>It=
=E2=80=99s very tempting to use the most popular Linux distributions as a b=
ase for docker containers. In fact, most of the time, that is actually a go=
od idea. However, when trying to build the most secure container possible, =
at the lowest possible size, these base images become bloat. Why include li=
braries and other binaries in your docker container if your application doe=
s not need them?
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/=
02/x509-certificate-manual-signature-verification/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">x509 Certificate Manual Signatu=
re Verification</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Feb 2, 2017
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p>Whi=
le going through the manual of <a href=3D"https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1=
.1.0/">openssl</a>, I thought it would be a good exercise to understand the=
 signature verification process for educational purposes. As a fruit to my =
labor, I would also develop a simple script to automate the process.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2017/=
01/ansible---interacting-with-external-rest-api/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Ansible - Interacting with exte=
rnal REST API</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Jan 1, 2017
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p>Ans=
ible has many powerful modules. One of which is called <a href=3D"http://do=
cs.ansible.com/ansible/uri_module.html"><strong>uri</strong></a> which is c=
apable of sending any kind of <code>HTTP</code> request. Using this module,=
 it is fairly simple to allow ansible to intelligently talk to a REST API. =
This will come in handy during for automation of the <a href=3D"https://sen=
suapp.org/">sensu</a> monitoring docker infrastructure I am currently worki=
ng on.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2016/=
12/openssl---reference/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">OpenSSL - Reference</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Dec 12, 2016
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p><a =
href=3D"https://www.openssl.org/">OpenSSL</a> is quite and extensive projec=
t. The docs for the <code>cli</code> (<a href=3D"https://www.openssl.org/do=
cs/man1.1.0/apps/">openssl commands</a>) gives you an overview on just how =
many things you can do with openssl. Knowing openssl is <strong><em>essenti=
al</em></strong> in the security field. I will use this post as a reference=
 for frequent things I do with openssl and update it when needed.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2016/=
07/hardening-nginx/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Hardening Nginx</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Jul 7, 2016
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p><a =
href=3D"https://www.nginx.com/resources/wiki/">Nginx</a> is a great web ser=
ver which offers very high performance with little resource consumption. Th=
is makes it ideal for docker containers, small embedded devices, or even ju=
st dealing with a ton of connections. I also often use Nginx=E2=80=99s powe=
rful proxy capabilities. Nginx is one of those applications I use quite oft=
en, pretty much for anything related to <code>http(s)</code>. Having said t=
hat, it becomes very important for me to be able to deploy this in a secure=
 manner.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2016/=
05/lets-encrypt-muli-domain-across-unique-ips/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Let's Encrypt Muli-Domain Acros=
s Unique IPs</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  May 5, 2016
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p><st=
rong>Let=E2=80=99s Encrypt is awesome!</strong> This service allows you to =
automate the retrieval of as many valid TLS certificates as you wish, as lo=
ng as you can <em>=E2=80=9Cprove=E2=80=9D</em> that you own the domain. One=
 of the first proofs that they offered was the <code>http-01</code> challen=
ge. This proof works by essentially sending your domain a random <code>HTTP=
 GET</code> request string which your lets-encrypt client must receive and =
send back.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2016/=
04/docker-storage-driver---devicemapper/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">Docker Storage Driver - Devicem=
apper</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Apr 4, 2016
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p>Doc=
ker relies on storage engines to layer images. The default storage driver d=
epends on who packaged docker for your OS. Fortunately, it=E2=80=99s not to=
o difficult to change; However you may lose your images and containers so i=
t=E2=80=99s best to decide on a driver when you begin.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
          <div class=3D"media">
           =20
            <div class=3D"media-body">
              <a class=3D"link-unstyled" href=3D"https://linuxctl.com/2016/=
04/memsql---cheatsheet/">
                <h3 class=3D"media-heading">MemSQL - Cheatsheet</h3>
              </a>
              <span class=3D"media-meta">
                <span class=3D"media-date text-small">
                  Apr 4, 2016
                </span>
              </span>
              <div class=3D"media-content hide-xs font-merryweather"><p><a =
href=3D"http://www.memsql.com/">MemSQL</a> is a cool distributed In-Memory =
Database which offers high performance, sharded horizontal scale-out design=
, High Availability (with <strong>Enterprise</strong> edition), and the fam=
iliar SQL syntax. It also ships with a great looking GUI that displays most=
 of information you need to know about your cluster.
</p></div>
            </div>
            <div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
            <hr>
          </div>
       =20
      </div>
    </div>
